While the economic effects are unknown, some initial reports indicated that, while the boycott failed to halt "business as usual", commerce slowed significantly in certain areas. According to the Los Angeles County Economic Development Corporation, the boycott cost the Los Angeles economy $52 million, 4.3 percent of the normal $1.2 billion daily activity.{{Fact|date=February 2007}}

In a show of solidarity, internationally, [[Trade union|labor unions]] and other groups engaged in a one-day boycott of American products called the "'''Nothing [[Gringo]] Boycott'''", particularly in [[Mexico]] and [[Central America]]n countries.<ref>{{cite news 
